{Since e4-e5 is serious strategic threat, Black's usual reaction to the
central expansion is ...dxe4, dxe4 ...e7-e5 with two possible scenarios. We
will first investigate the most aggressive of them, based on the positional
pawn sacrifice f4-f5.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. d3
b6 7. Qe1 Bb7 8. h3 Nbd7 9. Nc3 Re8 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 e5 12. f5 $1 gxf5 $6 (
{This is at least risky in most cases, but otherwise the kingside pressure
would be annoying. For instance:} 12... Nc5 13. Bg5 h6 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. Bxf6
Bxf6 16. b4 Nd7 ({Or if} 16... Na6 17. fxg6 fxg6 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 Qxb4 20.
d6 cxd6 21. Nd2 {wins material.}) 17. Qd2 Qxb4 18. fxg6 fxg6 19. Qxh6 Bg7 20.
Qg5 Nf8 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 $14 {followed by h3-h4.}) 13. Nh4 $1 ({The key
move, heading for play on light squares.} 13. exf5 $2 e4 $15 {would offer
Black active play in the centre.}) 13... fxe4 ({Or if} 13... Nxe4 14. Nxf5 Nec5
15. Bxb7 Nxb7 16. Bh6 $16) 14. Nf5 {Despite Black's two extra pawns White has
an overwhelming advantage due to the huge knight on f5.} Re6 15. Bg5 {White is
not in a hurry to retrieve one pawn as this would simplify the position a bit.}
Qf8 16. Rd1 Bc6 {Preparing the following move.} 17. g4 {Planning Qh4.} e3 $5 {
A desperate attempt at freeing his position.} 18. Bxc6 Rxc6 19. Qxe3 ({I
calculated} 19. Rxd7 Nxd7 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc6 {but thought that after} Qc5 {
the knight would be trapped. I missed the following sequence:} 22. Nd8 $3 e2+
23. Rf2 f6 24. Nf7+ Kg8 25. Nh6+ Kh8 26. Bc1 $18 {, keeping the extra piece.})
19... Re8 (19... Qc5 {runs into} 20. Qxc5 Rxc5 21. Be3 $18 {Black has to
sacrifice the exchange on c3 without real compensation, as if} Rc4 22. g5 {
wins a knight.}) ({Or if} 19... Kh8 20. Nxg7 Qxg7 21. Qf3 $18 {wins a rook.})
20. Bh6 {The start of the decisive attack, based on the seemingly paradoxical
exchange of the "bad" bishop.} Nxg4 (20... Bxh6 21. Nxh6+ Kh8 22. g5 {wins.})
21. hxg4 Bxh6 22. Nxh6+ Rxh6 23. Rxd7 Qg7 24. g5 Rh5 25. Ne4 Rh4 26. Rfxf7 1-0

