{The most natural way of fighting against White's central expansion is ...
d5-d4, in a moment when the White pawn is on d3 already. Depending on White's
reaction, this can lead to two typical structures. ***We shall first deal with
what I would call "The Dutch Benoni", when White plays c4.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6
3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 d4 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c3 {In the
Leningrad Dutch, this is the setup popularized by Malanjuk starting with the
'80s.} ({As mentioned in the database we can use our extra tempo in the Bird
opening to speed up our queenside play with} 9. c4 {But I have picked up this
game for two important reasons. First of all, I wanted to avoid quoting a game
used in the theory database already. Secondly, it makes sense to use a game of
the biggest expert of this structure ever.}) 9... Nd5 10. Bd2 e5 {Opening the
centre is one of the main plans. We will deal with the positions where Black
focuses on developing his queenside in the next example.} 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12.
Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Nc2 {The first critical moment. White has two main ideas: ...
cxd4 followed by Qf2 and c3-c4 followed by b2-b4. Black needs a certain
accuracy in order to deal with them both.} Bg7 $2 {This takes measures only
against the first threat, but completely neglects the second.} ({Things are
reversed with} 13... Rb8 $2 14. cxd4 $1 ({Black is safe after} 14. c4 Nf6 15.
b4 b6 {, even though White does not special reasons to complain either.}) 14...
cxd4 15. Qf2 Nf6 16. Bg5 (16. Bf4 {is less accurate due to} Ng4 17. Qf3 Be6 {
, and there is no clear way to win the pawn on d4 yet.}) 16... Kg7 (16... Ng4 {
runs into} 17. Qxf7+ Rxf7 18. Bxd8 {winning a pawn.}) 17. Bf4 {The pawn is
doomed as} Ng4 {allows} 18. Bxe5+ $1) ({But the correct solution to both
problems is} 13... a5 $1 {, preventing b2-b4 after c3-c4 and preparing an
elegant defence to the second threat:} 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Qf2 Nf6 16. Bg5 (16.
Bf4 {does not pin the bishop and is conveniently answered with} Ng4 17. Qf3 Bg7
) 16... Ra6 $1 {True, White could block the queenside with 14.a4 followed by
the knight transfer to c4 or b5. This would be more than OK with reversed
colours but with White one usually hopes for more.}) 14. c4 ({The idea behind
Black's last move is that} 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Qf2 {is parried with} Ne7 {
, since Bh6 is not available anymore.}) 14... Nf6 15. b4 cxb4 16. Nxb4 $16 {
A dream position for the Dutch/Bird Benoni. All White's minor pieces are
hyperactive, with the long diagonal and the d5-square available. It is worth
following the final (not very long) sequence until Black's collapse.} Ng4 17.
Nd5 Bd7 18. h3 Ne5 19. Qf2 Bc6 (19... Nc6 20. Rab1 b6 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. Qxf6
$16) 20. Bb4 Re8 21. Bc5 b5 22. Bxd4 bxc4 23. dxc4 f5 24. Rad1 Qa5 25. Bc3 Qxa2
$2 {Running into a small trick.} 26. Bxe5 Rxe5 27. Nb4 Qxc4 28. Nxc6 Rxe2 29.
Bd5+ Qxd5 30. Rxd5 1-0

