{[%evp 0,24,26,35,37,16,16,-54,29,29,13,4,0,-1,37,43,33,33,41,-7,-2,-48,-9,-92,
13,13,109]} 1. f4 c5 {If the opponent has the Sicilian Defence with Black in
his repertoire, one of the most probable reactions to the Bird is developing
in the spirit of the Closed Sicilian, irrespective of when and whether White
plays e2-e4. I must confess that for years this has been my main choice with
Black, too. White has no reasons to refrain from e2-e4, of course, as this is
the main idea in the Leningrad Bird. But in some cases delaying it may make a
difference in his favour. And even after e2-e4, he can choose between Nc3 and
c2-c3, depending on Black's concrete developing scheme. While Nc3 is typical
for the genuine Closed Sicilian, usually played on move two, to take measures
against ...d6-d5, c2-c3 is more flexible and keeps a better control in the
centre. I have occasionally played 1.e4 c5 2.d3 with White, always achieving
the same kind of positions as examined in this and the few next lines, but the
main problem with this move order is that Black can react with 2...d5 when
White has to be ready to play some reversed King's Indian scheme.} 2. Nf3 g6 3.
g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 {Black has three main setups at his disposal: ... d7-d6 followed
by ...e7-e5, ...e7-e6 followed by ...Nge7 and ...Nf6 (obviously, in
combination with ...d7-d6).} Nc6 5. O-O d6 {In this line we will examine the
system based on ...e7-e5, one of Botvinnik's favourite schemes, especially
with reversed colours (in the English Opening).} ({Since this line is very
much based on move orders, we should also mention} 5... e5 6. fxe5 Nxe5 7. Nxe5
Bxe5 8. c3 Ne7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg7 (10... Qb6 11. e3 Bg7 12. Nc3 $14 {
Szymczak,R (2037)-Kosny,M (1912) Poland 2015 (1-0, 78)}) 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bg5 (
12. e4 $5 d5 13. e5) 12... h6 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd5 $14 {With freer White
development in all lines.}) 6. d3 e5 {As we will see, this popular move order
is imprecise.} 7. fxe5 $1 {The most effective reaction. Delaying e2-e4 has not
only left the long diagonal open but also spared a tempo with respect to the
closed Sicilian schemes and two whole tempi with respect with the reversed
position in the English Opening. Therefore ha can afford to open the centre in
a moment when the black king is far from castling and the c5-pawn is hanging
slightly.} ({With this move order, White cannot force a transposition to Line
2 with} 7. e4 {due to} exf4 ({If} 7... Nge7 8. f5 {[%emt 0:00:02] transposes
to Line 2.}) 8. Bxf4 {This is the desired reaction to the capture on f4 in
Line 2, but with the e5-square well-defended Black can bravely take the pawn:}
Bxb2 9. Nbd2 Be5 $1 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Be3 b6 {Van Dooren,D (2331)-Gharamian,T 
(2517) Differdange 2007 (0-1, 32). White has certain compensation for the pawn
due to his bishops pair, but nothing concrete. The best continuation would
have been} 12. Qf3 f6 13. Nb1 Kf7 14. Nc3 Be6 {with unclear play.}) 7... dxe5 (
{Or if} 7... Nxe5 8. Nxe5 Bxe5 ({Safer than} 8... dxe5 {when c5 is likely to
become a target anyway.} 9. Be3 Qc7 10. Nc3 Rb8 11. Nd5 Qd6 12. c4 Bd7 13. b4
b6 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Qd2 $18 {The queenside pawns are as good as dommed and
the knig still needs some time to get castled, Movsziszian, K (2495) -Kropff,R
(2169) Barcelona 2016 (1-0, 24)}) 9. c4 Ne7 10. Nc3 $14 {White's better
control in the centre offers him very pleasant play.}) 8. Be3 {It is now when
the g2-bishop's activity is essential. Black has no easy way to defend c5, as .
..b7-b6 weakens the long diagonal.} Nd4 (8... e4 $5 9. Ng5 Nf6 10. c3 exd3 11.
Bxc5 $36 {with dangerous threats against the uncastled king.}) (8... b6 $2 9.
Nxe5 $1 {[%cal Rg2a8]}) (8... Qe7 9. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5]} Nf6 10. Bg5 {[%cal
Rc3d5,Rc3e4] threatening both Nd5 and Ne4 with strong initiative.}) 9. c3 Ne6 (
9... Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Qd6 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Qa3 {wins a pawn.}) 10. Nbd2 {Black
has defended the pawn at the cost of falling behind in development. White's
initiative continues with simple but effective moves.} Ne7 11. Ne4 {[%csl Rc5]}
Nf5 12. Bf2 Qc7 {Movsziszian,K (2499)-Kovchan,A (2577) Sitges 2013 (1-0, 42)}
13. b4 $1 $146 {The best way to keep the initiative going, with the enemy king
in the centre still.} cxb4 14. Qa4+ Bd7 15. Qxb4 $16 {White has a better
structure, clear queenside initiative and the black king did not castle yet.} *

