{[%evp 0,16,16,-29,6,4,51,-20,10,-24,-18,-16,32,23,18,-8,3,-33,-33]} 1. f4 (1.
e4 c5 2. d3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. f4 e6 6. Nf3 Nge7 {1-0 (37) Movsziszian,
K (2534)-Valmana Canto,J (2346) Albacete 2007}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4.
Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O e6 6. d3 Nge7 7. e4 O-O {A solid but slightly less active line
than the previously examined one. Black does not weaken his light squares so
easily.} 8. c3 {Since there is no pressure on e4 (the knight went to e7) White
does not need to over defend it with Nc3. The last move sustains d3-d4 and
restricts the bishop on g7.} d5 {This active move is surprisingly popular. It
offers White a very pleasant version of the French structure, as the bishop on
g7 is passive after e4-e5. And if Black tries to free it with ...f7-f6, the
weakness on e5 becomes an issue.} ({I will also mention a recent game of mine
with another pseudo active move:} 8... b5 9. Be3 Qb6 $2 10. e5 $1 {[%csl Rc5]
Causing Black big problems with defending c5.} (10. b4 $5 {is interesting but
not killing.} Nxb4 11. cxb4 Bxa1 12. Bxc5 Qd8 13. e5 $44) (10. d4 {This is
what Black had been preparing for.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 13. Qxd4
Qxd4+ 14. cxd4 Bb7 15. Nd2 f5 16. e5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Nd5 18. Rfc1 Rfc8 19. Nb3
$11 {Marin-Donchenko Chess Stars (rapid internet) 2019 (½-½, 44)}) 10... Nf5
11. Bf2 f6 12. b4 $16) ({The main continuation,} 8... d6 {is examined in the
next line.}) 9. e5 d4 {This gains even more space in the centre but conceals
the control over e4.} (9... b6 {is flexible but a bit passive. After
developing properly White can think of stabilizing the centre with d3-d4,
retaining a good control in the centre.} 10. Be3 Ba6 (10... Bb7 11. d4 cxd4 12.
cxd4 Qd7 13. Nc3 $14 {leaves Black completely without counterplay.}) (10... f6
11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Re1 Nf5 13. Bf2 $14 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c2,Yd3d4] followed by
Na3-c2 and finally d3-d4.}) (10... d4 $6 {is not too indicated with the long
diagonal weak.} 11. cxd4 Nf5 12. Bf2 cxd4 13. Nh4 $1 Qd7 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. Na3
Bb7 16. Nb5 Rad8 17. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb5d6] White is more active, the
intrusion Nd6 is unpleasant and the pawn on d4 in danger. Moreover, Black
cannot free himself easily as} f6 $2 {loses to} 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. e6 $18) 11.
Bf2 f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Re1 Qd6 14. d4 $1 cxd4 (14... Rae8 {is likely to
leave the centre hanging.} 15. Qa4 Nb8 16. Qa3 Rc8 17. Nbd2 Rc6 18. dxc5 bxc5
19. Rad1 Qc7 20. Nb3 Rc8 21. Na5 Rb6 22. b4 cxb4 23. cxb4 Bc3 24. Bc5 Rxb4 25.
Qxc3 Qxc5+ 26. Qxc5 Rxc5 {Berend,F (2345) -May,F (2020) Germany 1998 (1-0, 31)}
27. Rxe6 $16) 15. Nxd4 ({More ambitious than} 15. cxd4 Nb4 16. Bf1 Bxf1 17.
Kxf1 Rac8 18. Nc3 $14) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Rae8 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Nd2 Bd3 19.
Nf3 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Be4 {½-½ Gunsberger, A-Gheorghiu,F Bucharest 1966} 21. Ne5
Bxg2+ 22. Kxg2 $16 {With a great blockade for White.}) (9... f6 {does not
change the character of the position:} 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Re1 (11. Be3 d4 12.
Bf2 Nd5 {offers Black some counterchances, as White is slightly underdeveloped,
c3 is hanging and if cxd4 ...cxd4, ...Ne3 would become an issue.}) 11... Qd6
12. Na3 Bd7 13. Qe2 (13. Be3 $5 b6 14. Bf2 $14) 13... Rae8 14. Be3 a6 15. Bf2
b5 16. Nc2 b4 17. cxb4 cxb4 18. d4 $16 {Movsziszian,K (2534) -Valmana Canto,J 
(2346) Albacete 2007 (1-0, 37)}) 10. c4 f6 {Refraining from this means playing
with a piece down (the bishop on g7).} (10... Nf5 11. Na3 f6 (11... b6 $146 12.
Ng5 Bb7 13. Nc2 {[%cal Yg5e4] followed by Ne4 soon.}) 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Nc2 {
[%csl Ge3] Defending e3 in time.} Qd6 (13... e5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {
Mikac,T (2215)-Supancic,D (2375) Slovenia 1994 (0-1, 48)} 16. Bd2 a5 17. Qe2
$16) {Thomas,M-Kupsys,A ICCF corr 1994 (0-1, 38)} 14. Ng5 Bg7 (14... Bxg5 15.
fxg5 {Even though Black has an extra pawn in the centre, this is more of a
weakness than strength.} e5 16. g4 Ng7 17. Rxf8+ Qxf8 18. Qe2 Ne6 19. Bd5 Qd6
20. Bd2 Bd7 21. Rf1 Rf8 22. Ne1 $1 {Finally activating the knight.} Rxf1+ 23.
Kxf1 b6 24. Nf3 $16) 15. Bd2 {Preparing b2-b4.} a5 16. Qe2 Bd7 17. a3 a4 18.
Rab1 h6 19. Ne4 Qe7 20. b4 axb3 21. Rxb3 $14 {with better play on practically
all board areas.}) (10... b6 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Ne4 Rb8 13. Qe2 Ba8 {Stepovaia,T
(2384)-Molchanova,T (2368) St Petersburg 2009 (1-0, 46)} 14. g4 $16 {[%cal
