{[%evp 0,16,16,-29,6,4,51,-20,10,-24,-18,-16,32,23,18,-8,3,-33,-33]} 1. f4 (1.
e4 e6 2. d3 c5 3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 d6 7. c3 Nge7 8. Be3 O-O {
1-0 (21) Marcinkevicius,S-Sinnett,G ICCF corr 1994}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O e6 6. d3 Nge7 7. e4 O-O 8. c3 d6 {This is more flexible
than 8...d5, but it also leaves White with free hands in the centre.} 9. Be3 {
White continues developing and prepares to gain space with d3-d4. In this line,
we will examine two seemingly active moves, typical for the Closed Sicilian,
but a bit premature under the given circumstances.} b5 (9... f5 {is a direct
way of fighting against White's central expansion.} 10. exf5 $1 {This forces
Black to define his central structure in order to plan his own middlegame.}
Nxf5 {This avoids creating new weaknesses, but in the long run Black may lose
ground on the kingside, as White can consider g3-g4.} (10... gxf5 {White
maintains the compact character of his central structure, but in the long run,
this could turn into a weakness.} 11. Nbd2 $1 ({The best way of developing the
knight as} 11. Na3 {runs into} b5 {, possible due to the undefended pawn on b2.
}) 11... Bd7 (11... b5 {is less effective now. In fact, it just weakens c5:}
12. Bf2 b4 13. d4 $14) 12. Re1 Qc7 13. Bf2 Rae8 14. Rc1 $5 {[%cal Gd3d4,Gb2b4]
Preparing d3-d4 or b2-b4 and more or less forcing the queen to step away from
the potential pin.} Qb8 15. a4 $5 {White does not need to hurry at all, as
Black's position is rather rigid.} a6 16. Ng5 Rf6 (16... Nd8 {allows} 17. a5
$14) 17. Qb3 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra1 $14 {Black is hanging a bit.}) 11. Bf2
Bd7 12. Na3 Rb8 ({Or if} 12... Qc7 13. Re1 Rae8 14. Rc1 a6 {Braga,C (2370)
-Panno,O (2495) Sao Paulo 1993 (½-½, 47)} 15. d4 cxd4 16. cxd4 d5 17. Qd2 $14
) 13. Nc2 b6 14. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gd4c5] Threats such as dxc5 or d4-d5 more or
less force Black to take a decision.} cxd4 15. Ncxd4 Ncxd4 16. Nxd4 Qc7 17. Re1
Rbe8 18. Qd2 $14 {White's development is more harmonious and Black's central
pawns are hanging.} Bxd4 $6 {Strikovic,A (2520) -Sergeev,V (2417) Dos Hermanas
2004 (1-0, 62)} 19. cxd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] Threatening d4-d5.} d5 20. g4 Nd6 21.
Bg3 $16 {Black's weaknesses on dark squares put the king into a dangerous
situation.}) ({The main move} 9... b6 {is examined in the next line.}) 10. d4
cxd4 ({Black cannot keep the tension:} 10... Qb6 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Qd6 $16) 11.
cxd4 d5 {[%csl Rc5,Rg7] This leads to a typical French structure, where the
bishop does not have anything to do on g7. Moreover, c5 is weakened.} (11...
Bb7 {looks flexible, but it does not affect White's normal development.} 12.
Bf2 Rc8 13. Re1 a6 (13... Na5 14. Bf1 Qd7 15. a4 b4 16. Nbd2 $14) 14. Nc3 ({
This plans a global regrouping, but} 14. Bf1 $5 $14 {/\a4}) ({or} 14. a4 $5 $14
{are simpler.}) 14... Na5 15. Qe2 Nc4 16. g4 b4 17. Nd1 Qa5 18. Bh4 f6 {
Tu,H (2475)-Irzhanov,R (2500) Dubai 1996 (1-0, 32)} 19. f5 $5 {with certain
attacking chances.}) (11... f5 {is simplest met with} 12. e5 {Even though
Black has a blockade on d5, his bishop on g7 is not playing yet and c5 is weak.
} Nd5 13. Bf2 Bb7 14. Qe2 a6 15. Nbd2 Re8 16. Rac1 Bf8 $5 (16... dxe5 $6 {
This only weakens c5 and clears the diagonal for the bishop on f2.} 17. dxe5
$16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf2a7]} Qa5 18. Nb3 Qxa2 19. Nc5 Bc8 20. Ng5 Ncb4 21. Qd2
{1-0 (21) Marcinkevicius, S-Sinnett,G ICCF corr 1994} Qa5 22. Ncxe6 Bxe6 23.
Nxe6 Rxe6 24. Bxd5 $18) 17. a3 $5 ({Preparing the fight against c5. If} 17.
exd6 Na5 $1 {prevents Nb3.}) 17... Rc8 18. b4 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ye5d6,Yb3c5]
followed by Nb3 and later exd6 and Nc5.}) 12. e5 a5 13. Nc3 Ba6 14. Re1 Nc8 15.
Rc1 {Black's queenside counterplay is slow and does not have a clear thread.
White can either prepare a kingside pawn attack or simplify along the c-file
