{[%evp 0,16,16,-29,6,4,51,-20,10,-24,-18,-16,32,23,18,-8,3,-33,-33]} 1. f4 c5
2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O e6 6. d3 Nge7 7. e4 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. Be3
b6 {The most solid and by far most popular continuation. Black continues the
queenside development while also consolidating c5.} 10. d4 {As a general rule,
it is desirable to dispose over Nc3 after the exchange on d4. This is why it
makes sense to play this move with the knight on b1 still.} ({In practice,
White usually keeps manoeuvring for a while before opening the centre. Here is
a game which slightly shattered my confidence in Black's position (I must
confess that I used to play this line with both colours).} 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Bf2
Qc7 12. Na3 Rad8 13. d4 a6 14. Rc1 Rd7 15. Qe2 Rc8 {Deglmann,L (2285)-Marin,M 
(2528) Porto Mannu 2017 (½-½, 37)} 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Nc4 $14 {Compare with
similar positions in Line 6.}) 10... cxd4 {In the next lines we will examine
the lines in which Black refrains from this exchange at this stage.} 11. cxd4
Bb7 {Maintaining the own harmony before undertaking anything concrete.} ({
If we compare the position after} 11... d5 12. e5 {with the similar one with
the pawn on b5 (Line 4), we can notice that Black did not weaken the square on
c5, but at the same time his counterplay is even slower.} Ba6 (12... a5 {
is a bit slow:} 13. Nc3 Ba6 14. Re1 Qd7 {Vardanian,H (2268)-Martyn,R (2102)
Oropesa del Mar 2000 (1-0, 36)} 15. g4 b5 16. Rc1 Rfc8 17. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Gf4f5]
Preparing f4-f5.} f5 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Nf3 $14) 13. Re1 Qd7 14. Nc3 Nb4 $5 $146
({This is the only way to make use of the fact that, with respect to the Line
4, the f1-a6 diagonal is open. If} 14... Na5 15. Bf2 $146 Nc4 16. Qc1 Rac8 17.
b3 Na5 18. Qb2 $14 {Black does not achieve counterplay at all.}) 15. Bf1 $1 {
The simplest way to put an end to Black's counterplay. In principle, the
bishops' exchange slightly frees Black, but the play remains one-sided anyway.}
Bxf1 16. Rxf1 Rfc8 17. g4 Nbc6 18. Bf2 $14 {[%cal Gf2h4] Planning Bh4.} f5 19.
exf6 Bxf6 20. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1] Followed by Rae1 with enduring pressure.})
(11... f5 {can be answered in two reasonable ways:} 12. exf5 ({This tries to
take advantage of Black's relative vulnerability in the centre. A more solid
but quite promising alternative is} 12. e5 Nd5 13. Bf2 dxe5 {Clemens,C (2250)
-Zunker,R (2133) Eckernfoerde 2010 (½-½, 18)} 14. dxe5 Ba6 15. Re1 Qe7 16.
Qa4 Bb7 17. Nbd2 $14 {With freer play for White.}) 12... Nd5 13. Bf2 gxf5 14.
Re1 h6 15. Nc3 Nce7 16. Qb3 Qd7 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Rxe6 $1 Qxe6 19. Ng5 $16 {
Strikovic,A (2560) -Baches Garcia,G (2275) Mondariz 1997 (1-0, 56)}) ({If
Black does not block the centre with ...d6-d5, the consequences of the
seemingly active} 11... Ba6 {may be double-sided.} 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Nc3 Na5 14.
Bf2 Qd7 15. Rc1 Nc4 (15... Rfd8 16. d5 $16) (15... f5 16. exf5 {[%cal Gd4d5,
Gf3g5] followed by Ng5 and/or d4-d5.}) 16. Qe2 {It turns out that the knight
is pinned.} Qb7 17. b4 $1 {And now the bishop is exposed.} Qd7 (17... b5 18. d5
$1 $14) 18. a4 $14 {Terreaux, G-Roods, S CServe email 1995 (1-0, 39) White is
dominating all over the board.}) 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Bf2 ({White needs to display
some accuracy.} 13. Rc1 Na5 14. Bf2 {[%cal Gd1e2] allowed} Rxc3 $1 15. bxc3
Bxe4 {with excellent compensation for the exchange, as White's structure does
not look impressive at all now, Strikovic, A (2524)-Sokolov, A (2585)
playchess. com INT 2004 (0-1, 66)}) 13... Qd7 14. Re1 {Both sides have more or
less completed their development harmoniously and Black needs to find an
active plan in order to avoid being suffocated by White's centre.} Na5 15. Rc1
Rc7 16. Bh3 $5 {[%cal Gd4d5] With the strong threat d4-d5.} f5 (16... d5 17. e5
{looks more solid, but we knot that this structure favours White. The tempo
wasted on Bh3 is not essentially changing anything.}) 17. exf5 Nxf5 (17... Bxf3
18. Qxf3 Nxf5 19. Qe4 $14 {leaves Black hanging in the centre.}) 18. Ng5 Re8
19. g4 Nh6 20. Qe2 {Black has obviously lost the early middlegame battle and
now tries to complicate matters:} e5 21. d5 (21. dxe5 dxe5 22. Rcd1 Qc6 23. Nd5
$16) 21... Rcc8 $2 (21... Nf7 22. Nge4 $1 exf4 23. g5 $1 {The most effective
way to win the exchange.} Qxh3 24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. Qxe8+ Kg7 26. gxf6+ Kh6 27.
Qe4 $16) 22. f5 $1 $18 {The rest does not require special comments.} Nf7 (22...
gxf5 23. gxf5 Nxf5 24. Qh5 h6 25. Ne6 $18) 23. Ne6 g5 24. Bf1 Rc4 25. b3 Rcc8
26. Qe4 {1-0 Korolev,S-Semenyuk,V DDR 1982 White threatened both b3-b4 and Bb5.
} *

