{[%evp 0,16,16,-29,6,4,51,-20,10,-24,-18,-16,32,23,18,-8,3,-33,-33]} 1. f4 c5
2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O e6 6. d3 Nge7 7. e4 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. Be3
b6 10. d4 Bb7 {This and the next section are dedicated to the lines in which
Black refrains from an early exchange on d4. This is logical for at least two
reasons. First of all, he should not be in a hurry to give up his only central
outpost so easily, especially after having consolidated it with ...b7-b6.
Secondly, he could take on d4 only after White has moved his knight farther
from the optimal c3-square. True, in the latter case he needs to take piece
re-captures on d4, leading to some sort of open Sicilian in which the
combination of ...e7-e6 and ...g7-g6 is not necessarily effective, into
consideration.} 11. dxc5 {The most logical way of releasing the tension,
creating a target on c5.} ({If} 11. d5 exd5 12. exd5 Na5 {White experiences
problems with defending d5.}) ({And if} 11. Na3 {Black can switch to plan B
with} cxd4 12. Nxd4 ({The knight is not optimally placed for the structure
resulting after} 12. cxd4 Nb4 $5 $146 {and White does not seem to have
anything better than} 13. Nc2 Nxc2 14. Qxc2 {freeing Black's play.}) 12... Qd7
13. Qd2 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 {Sher, M (2520)-Ward, C (2490) Isle of Man 1994 (½-½,
22)} Bxd4+ 15. Qxd4 Rad8 16. Rad1 e5 $1 17. fxe5 (17. Qf2 exf4 18. gxf4 Qg4 {
[%cal Gf7f5] planning ...f7-f5.}) 17... Nc6 $1 18. Qxd6 {Otherwise ...Nxe5
with good play.} Qg4 19. Bf3 {Forced as the rook was hanging.} Qg5 20. Qf6 Qxe5
21. Qxe5 Nxe5 {White should return the pawn with 22.Be2=, as in case of} 22.
Bg2 Ba6 {Black has the initiative.}) 11... bxc5 {keeps better control in the
centre but leaves Black with a backward pawn on d6. The pawn on c5 is also
indirectly weak.} (11... dxc5 {leads to a favourable version of the Leningrad
structure. White has the potential threat e4-e5 followed by the invasion of
either f6 or d6 with a knight.} 12. Qe2 Qc7 (12... Qc8 13. Na3 Ba6 14. Nb5 e5
15. a4 $14 {White controls all the important squares.}) (12... e5 13. Na3 $14 {
is similar.}) 13. Na3 Rad8 14. Nb5 Qb8 15. e5 $14 {Fernandez,G (2223)-Marchena
Hurtado,J (2147) Zornotza 2014 (1-0, 36)}) 12. Na3 Na5 13. Qc2 Qc7 14. Rac1
Rfc8 15. Rfd1 {Black has completed his development and his main plans are
based on doubling the rooks on the d-file or breaking with b2-b4,} Qc6 16. Nh4
(16. Ne1 {looks more natural.}) 16... Qa6 (16... d5 17. e5 Rab8 18. Qf2 Bf8 19.
b3 $14 {As usual Black has little chances for counterplay with a blocked
centre.}) (16... Rab8 17. e5 {is similar.}) 17. Bf1 Qc6 18. Bg2 Qa6 19. Qd2 d5
(19... Rd8 {allows White to start his attack with} 20. g4) 20. e5 Nc4 21. Nxc4
Qxc4 22. b3 Qa6 23. Qf2 c4 24. b4 (24. g4 $5) 24... Qa4 25. Rb1 $1 $146 ({
Better than} 25. Bc5 Bf8 26. g4 a5 $132 {with counterplay in Jakubiec,A (2532)
-Antoniewski,R (2541) Poronin 2012 (0-1, 43)}) 25... a6 (25... a5 $2 {does not
work now due to} 26. b5 $16) (25... Bf8 26. g4 $16) 26. Nf3 $16 {White is in
complete control and after occupying the square on d4 can prepare his kingside
attack at the own leisure.} *

