b5 {The third alternative, possible only with the queen on a4.} 14. Qd1 Bxe4
15. cxd6 Nf5 16. Bc5 {[%cal Gd6d7] Threatening d6-d7.} Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Ne5 {
This leads to interesting complications favouring White.} 18. b4 Nd7 19. Bxa7
Nb6 20. d7 Nxd7 21. a4 e5 22. axb5 exf4 23. gxf4 Qh4 24. Rf1 {and the
queenside pawns are likely to tell.}) 14. Rd1 Rc7 15. Ne1 Rd7 16. Nxd3 Rxd3 17.
Na3 e5 18. f5 $16 {Renner,C (2412)-Haensel,T (2324) Apolda 2002 (½-½, 55)})
12... cxd4 {The principled answer, even though not an entirely satisfactory
one.} (12... Qc7 {can be answered with} 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 $14) 13. Nxd4
Nxd4 14. Bxd4 e5 {The typical Sicilian counterplay. The white knight is far
from d5 but the black knight is not standing too well either.} (14... Bxd4+ 15.
