{[%evp 0,16,25,-21,36,1,44,-32,-10,-26,-18,-38,-15,-23,0,-12,-12,-33,-17]} 1.
f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O Nf6 {We will talk in some detail
about this system in a comment a few moves later.} ({But since with his 8th
move White will prevent ...b7-b5, it makes sense mentioning that Black cannot
play it earlier under favourable circumstances:} 5... d6 6. d3 b5 7. Ne5 $1 {
wins material.}) (5... b5 6. e4 d6 7. c3 $1 Nf6 8. e5 Nd5 9. d4 {with
initiative in the centre.}) 6. d3 O-O 7. e4 d6 {Black has adopted a typical
Dragon structure, avoiding any weaknesses and losses of time. His main plan is
based on ...b7-b5-b4, controlling many important dark squares and hoping to
break with either ...c5-c4 or ..d6-d5. The main drawback of this system is
that it leaves Black with problems meeting the slow attack based on h2-h3,
g3-g4. If he does not find a way to open the queenside in his favour, his king
will be in danger some ten moves later.} 8. Nc3 {SInce Black's knight keeps e4
under pressure, I find the last move, transposing to a genuine closed Sicilian,
best. In the schemes with c2-c3 White exposes his pawn to ...b5-b4 and will
not find it easy to play d3-d4. Moreover, ...c5-c4 might disrupt his central
chain.} ({Here is a game in which an expert of these Closed Sicilians without
Nc3 (usually arising via 1.e4 c5 2.d3) went astray against the then World
champion:} 8. h3 b5 9. g4 a5 10. f5 b4 11. Qe1 Ba6 12. Qh4 c4 {It is clear
that Black's counterplay is very fast, while White's development is incomplete.
} 13. Bh6 cxd3 14. cxd3 Bxd3 15. Re1 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Ne5 18. Nbd2
Rac8 19. Ng5 Rc2 20. Rf1 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Rfc8 22. fxg6 hxg6 23. Nb3 Rxg2 24. Kxg2
Rc2+ 25. Kg3 Qe3+ {0-1 Fedorov,A (2575)-Kasparov,G (2845) Wijk aan Zee 2001.})
8... Rb8 9. h3 $1 {After many hesitations, I have chosen this as the most
promising move.} ({The main line is supposed to be} 9. a4 a6 10. h3 b5 11. axb5
axb5 12. Be3 b4 13. Ne2 Bb7 {but I do not like the idea of opening the a-file,
as it can be used by Black with ...Ra8 and if Rc1 then ...Ra2.}) 9... b5 10.
Be3 b4 ({I was curious to check what happens if Black delays ...b5-b4 while
carrying out the same plan as below:} 10... Nd7 11. Rb1 Qa5 $5 $146 {White
does not get the knight to c1 in time and the pawn on a2 is hanging to ...
b5-b4..} 12. a3 $1 {Logically, the only principled move.} Bxc3 {This is risky,
indeed, but there is no other way Black can justify his previous play. It
would take too long to retreat with the queen and renew the pawn attack with ..
.a7-a5 and ...b5-b4.} 13. bxc3 Qxc3 14. Qc1 b4 ({Black does not have all the
time in the world to prepare his attack. If} 14... a5 15. e5 Nd4 $5 16. Bd2
Ne2+ 17. Kf2 Nxc1 18. Bxc3 b4 19. Rfxc1 bxc3 20. Rxb8 Nxb8 21. exd6 exd6 22.
Ng1 {[%cal Gg1e2] followed by Ne2, Nxc3 and Rb1 with promising queenside play.}
) 15. Rb3 {is more ambitious.} (15. axb4 {is a risk free way to obtain
adequate compensation:} Rxb4 ({But not} 15... cxb4 16. e5 $1 {when} b3 {
is ineffective due to} 17. Rxb3 Rxb3 18. cxb3 {retrieving tha pawn with
obvious advantage. A fine point is that} Qxd3 {loses the hanging knight to} 19.
Ne1 {[%csl Rc6]}) 16. Bd2 Rxb1 17. Qxb1 Qa3 18. Qa1 Qxa1 19. Rxa1 $44 {Despite
the missing pawn White is obviously not worse. He has two bishops and an
advantage in the centre. But chances may be about equal.}) 15... Qg7 16. axb4
cxb4 17. Rb1 Nc5 18. Kh2 a5 19. Re1 f6 ({Black has to take measures as if} 
19... Ba6 20. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gf3d4] Planning d4-d5 followed by Nd4 with a
crushing space advantage.} Nxe4 21. d5 Nd8 22. Bd4 Nf6 23. Rxe7 $16) 20. f5 g5
21. d4 $5 Nxe4 22. d5 Nd8 23. Nd4 Nc3 24. Ra1 Ra8 25. Bd2 $14 {White will most
likely retrieve the pawns leaving Black in a passive position.}) 11. Ne2 Nd7 {
It makes sense to exert piece pressure on the queenside.} (11... a5 {deprives
Black of the play along the a-file:} 12. g4 ({Another possible move order is} 
12. Rb1 Bb7 13. g4 a4 14. Qd2 c4 15. b3 cxb3 16. cxb3 axb3 17. axb3 Nd7 18. d4
Na5 {Cabrilo,G (2458)-Eljanov, P (2665) Banja Vrucica 2006 (½-½, 26)} 19. Nh2
$1 Qb6 20. g5 Rfc8 21. Ng4 $16 {[%cal Gf4f5] followed by f4-f5 with a very
strong attack.}) 12... Ba6 13. f5 Nd7 14. Rb1 a4 15. g5 ({White has to avoid} 
15. Qd2 c4 16. d4 c3 $1) 15... Qa5 (15... Nde5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. h4 {[%cal
Gh4h5] followed by h4-h5 also offers good attacking chances.}) 16. b3 (16. h4
c4 17. Nf4 $14) 16... Nde5 {Khokhlov,I (2381)-Pranjic,M (2387) ICCF email 2009
(0-1, 38)} 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. h4 {Black does not have a clear queenside plan
and can do very little to parry White's slow kingside attack. For instance} e6
$6 19. f6 {[%cal Gh4h5] planning h4-h5 leads to trouble.} h5 $2 ({This only
makes things worse, the same as} 19... h6 $2 20. h5 $1) 20. Bf3 Rfc8 21. Bxh5
$1 gxh5 22. Nf4 $18 {with a decisive attack.}) 12. Rb1 Qa5 13. Nc1 {White's
queenside position looks passive but Black does not have an obvious plan of
continuing. At the same time, the plan starting with g3-g4 is running at
leisure.} Ba6 (13... Nb6 {Bartel,M (2302)-Kanarek,M (2484) Warsaw 2012 (0-1,
47)} 14. f5 Na4 (14... gxf5 15. Nh4 $1 {offers White a very strong attack:}
fxe4 16. Bxe4 Ne5 17. Qh5 Ng6 18. Bh6 Bd7 19. Ne2 Qxa2 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Nf4
$18) 15. Nb3 Qc7 16. Qc1 Nb6 17. Bh6 {Things are under control on the
queenside and the attack has made some progress on the opposite wing.}) 14. Re1
(14. Rf2 {is also possible:} Qc7 15. Ne2 Rfc8 16. f5 Nce5 17. Nf4 Bb7 {Hrabal,
M (2100)-Vanek,L (2181) Czechia 2013 (0-1, 32)} 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. h4 {[%cal
Gg2h3,Gg3g4] followed by Bh3 and g4-g5.}) 14... Qc7 {Visser,Y (2455)-Nijboer,F
(2565) Netherlands 2001 (0-1, 36)} 15. g4 $1 $146 {While Black is short of
constructive ideas, White's attack is advancing slowly but surely.} *

