{[%evp 0,29,29,-23,-16,-8,-8,-2,-12,-12,11,11,35,36,36,18,18,6,6,13,13,20,74,
45,83,56,100,91,92,63,84,77]} 1. f4 e5 {I had good reasons to place the From
Gambit so high in the variations' hierarchy. I believe that many players
consider the Bird Opening risky mainly because of this gambit and during my
early experimenting with this opening I always transposed to the King's Gambit
with 2.e4 when I faced the gambit. Just a few days before I played the game
mentioned in the next line, I had a talk with Karen Movsziszian about the Bird
in general. Karen usually transposes to it after 1.g3 and 2.Bg2 and he
confessed to me that he would not know what to do after 1.f4 e5. When I faced
the gambit a few days earlier against a lower-rated, but apparently prepared
and confident opponent, I took it as a test to myself to retain an advantage
despite knowing virtually nothing about it. I was mainly hoping on a slightly
earlier conversation with my friend GM Lupulescu. Costica told me: "You should
just take the pawn!" While the gambit surely is interesting, White should be
able to stay on top, even though sometimes he has to return the pawn for this
purpose. I should also mention that while the gambit is enormously popular at
club level, there are few games between strong players with it.} ({Another
move order to reach the main tabiya is} 1... d6 2. Nf3 e5 3. fxe5 dxe5 4. Nxe5
Bd6 (4... Qh4+ {does not yield anything after} 5. g3 Qe4 6. Nf3 $16) 5. Nf3 {
transposing below.}) 2. fxe5 d6 3. exd6 Bxd6 4. Nf3 {This is the initial
gambit tabiya. Optically, the white kingside is exposed, but Black's advance
in development is not such that really causes trouble. Besides, White only
needs to advance his central pawns in order to obtain an improved version of
the King's Gambit, meaning with an extra pawn!} Nf6 {In this line we will
examine natural black developing moves.} (4... Nc6 {simplifies White's
developing plan:} 5. d4 Bg4 6. e3 Qe7 7. Bb5 $14) ({Fighting for space with} 
4... c5 {consumes too much time:} 5. e4 Nc6 {Sangiamo,J-Fink,S (2270)
Philadelphia 1992 (1-0, 23)} 6. Bc4 Nf6 7. O-O $16 {We have reached the
aforementioned improved King's Gambit.}) (4... Bg4 5. e4 $5 ({This leads to
entertaining play, but White can transpose to 5...Bg4 below with} 5. e3) 5...
Qe7 6. Nc3 f5 7. Qe2 Nc6 8. exf5 Bxf3 (8... Ne5 9. Nd5 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 Bxf3 11.
Nxe7 Bxe2 12. Bxe2 Nxe7 {Companyo Pagerols, J (2090)-Villa Izquierdo, R (2161)
Barbera del Valles 2008 (0-1, 63)} 13. f6 gxf6 14. d4 $14 {Another King's
Gambit pattern. The pawns are equal but White has obtained his usual central
majority and has two bishops.}) 9. gxf3 Nd4 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 11. f6 {In the
online database the game Kloss-Felbecker, H corr 1997 ends here without a
result. I have analyzed the following variation:} gxf6 12. Kd1 O-O-O 13. Ne4 {
By returning the pawn White has chances to retain a small plus.} Nxf3 (13...
Nd5 14. Nxd6+ Rxd6 15. c3 Nxf3 16. d4 Re8 17. Bh3+ Kb8 18. Bg4 {with the
better structure.}) 14. Be2 Nd4 15. Bc4) ({The crucial} 4... g5 {is examined
in the next example.}) 5. e3 Ng4 {The most active move, retrieving the pawn
more or less by force. The immediate threat is ...Nxh2.} (5... O-O 6. Be2 c5 {
is positionally sound but a bit slow:} 7. O-O Nc6 8. b3 $1 {The best way to
anticipate an attack based on ...Bb8, ... Ng4, ...Qd6. White immediately puts
the f6-knight under observation.} Be6 9. Bb2 Qe7 (9... Ng4 10. Nc3 f5 11. Bc4
$16) 10. Bb5 Rac8 11. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1h4] followed by Qh4 and neutralizing all
the attacking chances.}) ({Or if} 5... Bg4 6. Be2 O-O (6... Nc6 7. d4 {
restricts the enemy knight and gains space in the centre.}) 7. c4 c5 8. Nc3 Nc6
9. O-O {and White can enjoy the extra pawn without being in real danger.}) 6.
d4 $1 {A useful move, indirectly parrying the initial threat.} Qe7 (6... Nxh2
$2 {does not work due to} 7. Nxh2 Qh4+ 8. g3 $1 {Clearing the second rank with
a gain of time.} Bxg3+ 9. Kd2 {This is the main idea behind d2-d4.} Bxh2 10.
Qe2 $18) 7. Nc3 $1 $146 {White can defend the pawn on e3 only by falling
behind in development. By returning it, he can get a typical King's Gambit
structure with preferable chances.} Nxe3 8. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 c6
(10... O-O 11. Nb5 $14) 11. Ne4 Be7 12. O-O Bf5 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Rfe1 $1 {
Why precisely this rook will be revealed soon.} Bxe4 ({If} 14... Nd7 15. Nc5 $1
{the rook does not hang on f1 to ...Bxd3.} Nxc5 16. Bxf5 Ne6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18.
Rxe6 $16) 15. Rxe4 $14 {With pleasant play for White.} *

