Qe7 11. Bg2 Be6 12. Nd2 $14 {Lie,K (2560)-Sulskis,S (2577) Porto Carras 2011 
(0-1, 48)}) 7... Ng6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Ne4 {Just in time to parry ...Bxg3+.} (9.
Bg2 {defends the rook but obstructs the second rank, allowing} Rxh2 10. Rxh2
Bxg3+) 9... f5 ({The other way of attacking the knight is} 9... Bf5 10. Nxd6+
Qxd6 11. d3 {Restricting the bishop on f5 and preparing Bf4.} Nc6 12. Bg2 O-O-O
(12... Rxh2 $2 {does not work because of the intermediate} 13. Bxc6+ {clearing
the second rank.} bxc6 14. Rxh2 Qxg3+ 15. Rf2 Qg1+ 16. Rf1 Qg3+ 17. Kd2 $18) {
Van Dooren,D (2308)-Kabos,T (2122) Dieren 2009 (½-½, 78)} 13. Bf4 Qc5 (13...
Qb4+ 14. Qd2 Qxb2 15. O-O {allows White to start his attack quicker} Rh5 16.
Rab1 Qa3 17. Rf2 Rdh8 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Rb3 Qe7 20. c4 $18) 14. Qd2 Rxh2 (14...
Nb4 15. O-O-O Nxa2+ 16. Kb1 Nb4 17. Qc3 Qxc3 18. bxc3 Nd5 19. Bd2 $14) 15. Rxh2
Qg1+ 16. Bf1 Qxh2 17. O-O-O $14 {White has two bishops and a compact structure.
}) (9... Be5 {fails to molest the knight as it has the retreating square on f2.
} 10. c3 f5 (10... c5 11. Bg2) 11. Nf2 (11. d4 fxe4 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Bf5
{is only symbolically better for White, as his bishops do not have obvious
ways to break Black's fortress.}) 11... c5 12. Qb3 {Black will face some
problems completing his development now while White's position is solid.} Nc6
13. Bg2 Qe7 14. d3 Be6 15. Bg5 $1 Qd7 16. Qb5 Bd6 17. O-O-O Rh5 18. Be3 $14) (
9... Be7 {is more passive than 9...Be5.} 10. d4 f5 11. Nf2 Nc6 12. c3 Bd6 (
12... Qd5 13. e4 fxe4 14. Bg2 Bf5 15. Qb3 $16 {wins the pawn on e4.}) 13. Qd3
Bd7 14. Bg2 Qe7 15. h4 $16 {Black has little to show for the missing pawn,
