{[%evp 0,23,28,-29,-29,-29,14,-5,-26,-22,-7,-21,-11,-6,0,7,18,13,19,17,26,1,41,
31,32,37]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 ({White cannot take measures against ...Bg4, as} 2.
g3 h5 {is likely to cause problems.} 3. Nf3 (3. h3 {allows} e5 4. fxe5 Qg5 {
[%csl Re5,Rg3] with a double attack on e5 and g3.}) 3... h4 $1 4. Nxh4 Rxh4 5.
gxh4 e5 {and Black will soon have a pawn for an exchange and strong initiative.
}) 2... Bg4 {During the months when I played the Bird without preparing, the
thought that my opponent could choose this system was not less worrying than
the From Gambit. The point is that White cannot adopt the Leningrad setup
anymore while the schemes with e2-e3 are supposed to be slightly less
ambitious. And yet, the bishop's exposure on g4 is also an important factor.}
3. e3 (3. g3 Bxf3 4. exf3 {leaves Black with the better structure. Unlike in
the 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 d5 4.Bxf6 Dutch, the queen's knight does not block the
c-pawn so Black can achieve a harmonious development.}) 3... Nd7 {This is
connected with the plan of opening the centre with ...e7-e5 soon.} ({
Alternatively, Black can opt for a normal course of development with} 3... e6 {
planning ...c7-c5 and so on.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 c5 ({Preventing Bb5 with} 5...
a6 {offers White a free tempo.} 6. Be2 c5 7. d3 Nc6 8. c3 {Controlling d4
before advancing the e-pawn.} Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 $14 {With consistent
strategic initiative.}) 6. Bb5+ $1 {Aiming to spoil Black's coordination a bit.
} Nd7 (6... Nc6 {leaves White with the better structure after} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8.
b3 {In the spirit of the Queen's Indian Dutch.} Be7 9. Bb2 Bf6 10. Nc3 Ne7 11.
g4 $5 Bh4+ 12. Kd1 O-O 13. Na4 c4 14. Rf1 {White's structure is more flexible
and his threats against the enemy king are likely to take concrete contours
earlier than Black's.}) 7. O-O a6 ({Another possible move order is} 7... Ngf6
8. g4 a6 9. Be2 {[%cal Gc2c4] planning c2-c4.} c4 10. d3 cxd3 11. cxd3 $14) 8.
Be2 Ngf6 9. d3 $14 {In both last lines White's play is freer and his expansion
plans are quite natural.}) 4. h3 {This is the simplest way to retain the more
pleasant position.} ({Whenever the thought came up that my opponent could play
2...Bg4 I mentally worked out some schemes starting with} 4. Be2 {I actually
played two games with it, which I will present here, just to offer a wider
perspective over this whole system.} c6 (4... Ngf6 5. O-O e6 6. d3 c6 7. Qe1
Qc7 8. Nc3 {White has developed in the spirit of the Iljyin Zhenevsky Dutch,
planning e3-e4.} Bd6 {... which is not that easy to carry out now.} 9. Bd2 h6
10. Nd4 Bxe2 11. Ncxe2 a6 ({Anticipating my intention:} 11... O-O-O $6 12. Ba5
$1 b6 13. Bc3 g5 14. b4 {[%csl Rb6] and the weakness on b6 will tell.}) 12. b4
g5 13. a4 Rg8 14. Kh1 Qd8 15. Nc1 $1 {Improving the placement of the so far
worst white piece.} Qe7 16. Ncb3 $14 {White has better control over the
important squares and his king is safer, Marin, M (2525)-Piorun, K (2656)
Benasque 2019 (½-½, 20)}) 5. O-O Bxf3 6. Bxf3 e5 7. d4 $5 {White does not
wish to conceal space to his opponent.} e4 (7... exf4 8. exf4 Bd6 9. c4 dxc4
10. d5 $14) 8. Be2 {White's position is easier to play, as he has plans on
both wings: c2-c4 and g2-g4.} Ngf6 9. b3 Be7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 Rc8 12. g4 Nb6
13. c5 Nbd7 14. b4 b6 15. Bd2 Ne8 16. Kh1 f5 17. gxf5 Rxf5 18. Bg4 Rf8 19. Be1
Rc7 20. Be6+ Kh8 21. f5 Bh4 22. Qg4 Bxe1 23. Raxe1 Ndf6 {Marin,M (2522)
-Jakobsen,P (2250) Lund 2019 (1-0, 41)} 24. Qh3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4]
followed by Ne2-f4.}) 4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3 {White has not only got the bishops'
pair but also prepared a kingside attack with g2-g4.} c6 ({The other way to
defend d5 and maintain the threat of ... e7-e5 is} 5... Ngf6 6. g4 e5 ({
Refraining from opening the centre leaves White with very pleasant play after} 
6... e6 7. d3 h6 8. e4 c6 9. Be2 $14) 7. Nc3 $5 $146 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yg4g5]
Attacking d5 and defending e4, in order to threaten g4-g5 under optimal
circumstances.} e4 (7... c6 8. g5 Ng8 9. h4 $16 {leaves Black with developing
problems.}) (7... exf4 8. g5 Ne5 9. Qxf4 Bd6 10. Kd1 $1 {Parrying ...Nd3+.} Nh5
11. Qh4 g6 12. Nxd5 $14 {The king is safe behind the pawn wall so Black does
not have much of a compensation for the pawn.}) 8. Qg2 c6 9. g5 Ng8 10. b3 $5 {
A good moral compensation for having denied the other bishop's fianchetto.} g6
11. Bb2 Bg7 12. O-O-O Ne7 13. h4 h5 14. gxh6 Rxh6 15. h5 $14) 6. d4 $1 {
Now that the black knight is not in time for invading e4, this is the best way
to stop ...e7-e5. White's structure becomes typical for the Stonewall Dutch,
with the difference that Black's pressure in the centre is absent (he would
need the pawn on c5 and knight on c6 for it). White has two bishops and fluent
kingside play.} Ngf6 (6... f5 {fails to help to invade the e4-square.} 7. g4 e6
8. Bd3 ({Abstractly it looks best to force ...g7-g6 but if White wishes to
maintain the right to castle he can play} 8. g5 Bd6 9. c4 Ne7 10. Nc3 $14) 8...
g6 (8... Qh4+ 9. Kd1 g6 10. Bd2 {Threatening g4-g5 more or less trapping the
queen.} h6 11. c4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qe7 13. Nc3 Ngf6 14. Kc2 Nb6 15. Bb3 O-O-O 16.
Rae1 $14 {With a favourable version of the 4.e3 Bg4 Slav as White is
completely in control.}) 9. g5 Bd6 10. h4 h5 11. O-O Ne7 12. b3 Qc7 13. Bb2
O-O-O 14. c4 e5 $5 15. Qf2 (15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. fxe5 Bxe5 {leaves White hanging.}
) 15... e4 16. Be2 $14 {At this height it is obvious that only White has
active plans.}) 7. Bd3 g6 {The typical Anti Dutch setup.} (7... e6 8. O-O Bd6
9. c4 $146 O-O 10. Nc3 $14 {Apart from the kingside plan, typical for the
Stonewall, White also has more space in the centre.}) 8. O-O Bg7 9. Nd2 ({
If White intends to display ambitions in the centre he can also try} 9. b3 O-O
10. Bb2 c5 11. Nd2 Rc8 12. c4) 9... c5 10. c3 O-O 11. g4 e6 12. g5 Ne8 (12...
Nh5 13. Qg2 $14 {exposes the knight to Be2.}) 13. h4 Nd6 14. h5 $14 {[%cal
Gg1g2,Gf1h1,Gf3h3,Gd2f3] White's attack may become threatening soon (Kg2, Rh1,
Qh3, Nf3) while Black's queenside play has not even started yet.} *

