{[%evp 0,20,16,-8,-24,-35,-22,-38,-47,-53,-11,-7,-14,-35,11,0,31,-40,-54,-54,
-54,15,27]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 {We now start investigating the schemes based
on Black's king's fianchetto, which should be considered the main lines, if we
think that this (in fact g2-g3) is the most popular setup against the Dutch in
general.} 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nh6 {This and the next two lines are dedicated to
the systems based on this original way of developing the knight. In principle,
Black intends to meet d2-d3 ...Nf5 and ...d5-d4, in order to inhibit e2-e4.
With the knight on f5, ...h5-h4 is a possible plan, too. The main drawback of
this plan is that if Black fails to hold the blockade, the knight will be
vulnerable. And White's extra tempo with respect to the Leningrad Dutch makes
itself felt.} 5. d3 d4 ({If} 5... Nf5 6. c3 ({Actually, the immediate} 6. e4 {
also offers White some chances for at least the more pleasant position:} dxe4
7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nd4 9. Nxd4 Bxd4 10. c3 Bb6 {Otherwise the bishop would
be exposed to being cut off the play with e4-e5.} 11. Kc2 Be6 12. Nd2 Nc6 13.
b4 {White's pawn play is clearer than Black's.}) 6... c5 (6... d4 {transposes
below.}) 7. e4 {with the d4-square under control this is even more effective.}
dxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Nh6 ({The knight does not have favourable paths at
its disposal.} 9... Nd6 10. e5 Nc4 11. b3 Na5 12. Ba3 Na6 13. Nbd2 $14) 10. Be3
b6 11. h3 Bb7 12. Nbd2 Nd7 13. Kc2 {[%cal Gg2f1,Ga2a4] followed by a2-a4 and
possibly Bf1-c4/b5.}) 6. c3 Nf5 ({If} 6... c5 7. e4 dxe3 8. Bxe3 {Black needs
to spoil his coordination a bit in order to defend c5.} Nd7 (8... Qb6 9. Qe2
Ng4 10. Bg1 O-O 11. Na3 Rd8 12. Ng5 h6 13. Ne4 {White will soon gain a few
tempi for his initiative with h2-h3, g3-g4, Nc4. He will also have a choice
