g3-g4 soon also offers White pleasant play.}) 9. h3 Nf5 10. Bf2 Qc7 (10... h5 {
prevents g4 but weakens g5.} 11. Nbd2 Qc7 12. Ne4 b6 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. Nfg5 {
with kingside pressure.}) 11. g4 Nd6 12. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gf2g3,Yf4f5]
Followed by Qe2, Bg3 and eventually f4-f5. Depending on how his kingside
attack develops, White could also consider castling long.}) 7. O-O ({More
flexible than} 7. g4 {, which leads to interesting play, too:} Ne3 8. Bxe3 dxe3
9. Qc1 Bxg4 10. Ne5 Bc8 11. Qxe3 {White's better development and central
control at least compensates for Black's bishops' pair.}) 7... c5 ({If} 7...
O-O {White can already play} 8. g4 Ne3 9. Bxe3 dxe3 {since he now can defend
his kingside pawns and win the pawn on e3:} 10. h3 Qd6 11. Ng5 $1 {This is
when the rook on f1 was needed.}) (7... h5 {loses time and weakens the
kingside a bit. White could deviate from the standard plans with} 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
({Black's initiative after} 8... Bxd4+ 9. cxd4 Qxd4+ 10. Rf2 h4 {is illusory:}
11. g4 h3 12. Be4 Nh6 13. e3 Qb6 14. g5 Nf5 15. Nc3 Na6 16. d4 c6 17. Rb1 $14)
9. cxd4 Qxd4+ 10. e3 Qb6 11. Nc3 c6 12. d4 {We have reached some sort of
