works out well only after the knight has developed to d7. Otherwise, it would
be too close to d4 and b4.} Rac8 (11... d4 12. a5 {[%cal Gb2b4] followed by
b2-b4 offers White excellent queenside play.}) (11... Rad8 12. a5 $5) 12. Rc1
Qb8 13. cxd5 ({The main problem with} 13. Ng5 {[%cal Ge2e4] (planning e2-e4)
is allowing the early bishops exchange after} d4 (13... e5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. f5
{looks just great.}) 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. e4 dxe3 16. Bc3 {The position remains
interesting, but I trust this plan less than that in the main line.}) 13...
Nxd5 14. Nc4 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Rfd8 (14... e5 $6 {is bad for many reasons.} 15.
Bh3 (15. f5 $14) (15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Ncxe5 Bxe5 17. e4 Nb4 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Bc3
$14) 15... f5 16. e4 $14) 15. e4 {Forcing matters a bit.} (15. b3 $5) (15. Qf2
$5) 15... Nb4 {Otherwise White would have more space and the black knights
would still be far from d4.} 16. Bxb4 cxb4 17. d4 (17. Qxb4 $2 Nc5 $1) 17...
Qa8 18. e5 {[%csl Rg7] This looks more like a Gruenfeld, but the main thing is
that the bishop on g7 is quite passive. I find White's position more pleasant.}
*

