{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 {This is the most natural way of developing for Black, corresponding
to the Leningrad Dutch main system.} 7. Qe1 {The plan based on 7...Qe8 became
popular sometime during the late '70s and the '80s and I believe it remains
the most fluent up to today. White immediately threatens e2-e4.} (7. c3) (7.
Nc3) 7... d4 {Played in the spirit of the absolute main line in the Leningrad
Dutch 7...Qe8 system. Black prevents White from creating two connected pawns
in the centre but at the same time he opens the long diagonal as well as some
other light squares.} ({The main alternative,} 7... Nc6 {, will be examined
later.}) 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c4 $5 {This is one of the lines when White can really
use the extra tempo in order to speed up his plans even more.} (9. Bd2 Rb8 10.
c3 {possibly followed by Nc2 and c3-c4 is similar to what Black does in the
Dutch. But if we compare to the recommended line, White gains a tempo with his
c-pawn and does not expose himself to the exchange ...dxc3 during a long phase.
}) {We will investigate Black's main continuations one by one.} 9... dxc3 10.
bxc3 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] White has a compact central structure, but Black
intends to undermine it with ...b7-b5 followed by either ...b5-b4 or ...c5-c4
in the near future. Due to his extra tempo, White can prevent this.} 11. Rb1 b6
{White's compact pawns have enormous latent energy. But it is important to
plan every pawn move carefully, as a single unnecessary weakness could result
in the crumbling down of the whole structure.} 12. Nc2 ({I slightly prefer
these continuations, aiming at improving the queenside position to the
aggressive} 12. h3 Bb7 13. g4 {which looks playable, too.} e6 ({If} 13... Nd5
14. Bd2 Qd7 15. Rd1 Rbd8 16. Nc2 {and e2-e4 is in the air already.}) 14. Nc4
Nd5 15. Bd2 f5 16. e4 {This leads to some complications resulting in
simplifications and a draw.} fxe4 17. Qxe4 (17. Ng5 $5 Qd7 18. Nxe4) 17... Nxc3
18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Bxc3 Bxc3 20. Nd6 Qf6 21. Qxf6+ (21. Ng5 $5) 21... Bxf6 22.
Nxb7 Rxb7 23. Ne5 Bxe5 24. fxe5 Rxf1+ 25. Rxf1 Rc7 26. Bxc6 Rxc6 27. Rf7 {
½-½ Koc,P (2330) -Novikov,I (2545) Koszalin 1998}) 12... Bb7 13. c4 {Since ..
.e7-e5 would weaken the d5-squares chronically, Black is somewhat short of
active plans.} Qc7 (13... Qd7 14. Bb2 Rbd8 15. Rd1 Ne8 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. e3 {
followed by Qc3 and, depending on Black's plan, d3-d4 or e3-e4.}) 14. Bb2 ({
Since there is no pressure on d3,} 14. e4 {comes into consideration. The
weakness on d4 is not relevant as it is well defended by White's minor pieces,
while e4-e5 will strongly restrict Black's pieces.} Rbd8 15. e5 Ne8 16. Rb3 {
The rook not only defends d3 but also inhibits any plan based on ...b6-b5.} f6
(16... Na5 17. Ra3) 17. Bb2 {White retains active play, as Black cannot really
free himself with} fxe5 18. Ng5 Na5 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 (19... Nxb3 20. Bd5+ Rxd5 21.
cxd5 $16) 20. Qxa5 h6 21. Ne4 Qxe4 22. dxe4 bxa5 23. Bxe5 Bxe5 24. fxe5 Rxf1+
25. Kxf1 {with persisting initiative in the endgame.} Rd2 26. Ne3 Ng7 27. Rb7
Rxh2 28. Nd5 Rxa2 29. Nxe7+ Kh7 30. Rxa7 $14) 14... Rbd8 15. Ne3 (15. Rd1 $5)
15... e6 16. Nc2 {This looks like a waste of time, but Black has very few
ideas to use it. Besides, the weakness induced by ...e7-e6 may count later.}
Rfe8 17. Bc3 Ba8 18. Rb3 Bb7 {It is obvious that Black does not find a
concrete plan.} 19. Qa1 Nh5 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. fxe5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 {White has
some concrete advantage and a clear kingside plan already.} Bh6 23. Rf3 Qc6 24.
Rb1 Rd7 25. Rbf1 Rb8 26. Kg1 Bf8 27. Ne3 Ng7 28. Ng4 Ne8 29. Qc1 $16 {Jakubiec,
A (2524)-Piorun,K (2353) Krakow 2007 (1-0, 44)} *

