{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 d4 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c4 Ng4 {In the position with reversed colours
(and an extra tempo for White) this would cast serious doubt over ...c7-c5.
But here White is just in time to defend e6 and prepare the queenside
counterplay.} 10. Nc2 Rb8 {Preparing ...b7-b6.} ({Black cannot develop his
initiative yet:} 10... e5 11. h3 {wins a pawn.}) (10... Re8 {allows White to
undermine Black's centre with} 11. h3 Nh6 (11... Ne3 12. Nxe3 dxe3 13. Bxe3
Bxb2 14. Rb1 Bd4 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Bd2 $16) 12. b4 $14) {Montigel,P-Zimber,A
Wuerttemberg 1994 (½-½, 42)} 11. h3 {Now is a good moment to force the
knight to take a decision.} Nh6 (11... Nf6 12. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] Preparing
b2-b4.} a5 13. g4 (13. e4 {is another interesting idea} dxe3 14. Bc3 {With
active play, as if} Qxd3 15. Nxe3 {the queen will soon land onto a very
passive position, handing in the initiative to White.}) 13... b6 14. Na3 Bb7
15. Nb5 e6 16. Qg3 {with good control all over the board.}) 12. Bd2 b6 13. Qf2
Bb7 14. g4 {I have analyzed a few illustrative lines.} f5 {Parrying threats as
f4-f5 and anticipating Ng5.} 15. Ng5 Qd7 16. Bd5+ Kh8 17. Qh4 {A typical case
with molesting white initiative.} Nd8 (17... fxg4 18. hxg4 Qxg4+ 19. Qxg4 Nxg4
20. Nf7+ Rxf7 21. Bxf7 $14) 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 19. gxf5 Qxf5 20. e4 $14 dxe3 21. Bc3
$1 Ndf7 22. Nxe3 Qd7 (22... Qxd3 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Ne6+ Kg8 25. Rae1 Re8 26.
f5 Rd7 27. f6 $16) 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Ng4 {[%cal Ga1e1]} Rh8 25. f5 Nxf5 26.
Rxf5 gxf5 27. Re1 e5 28. Rxe5 Qd4+ (28... Nxe5 29. Qh6+ Kg8 30. Nf6#) 29. Kh1
Qxe5 30. Nxe5 Nxe5 31. Ne6+ Kf7 32. Qh6 $16 *

