{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 d4 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c4 e5 {With reversed colours, this would have
been another typical reaction. But here, too, the extra tempo Na3, bringing
the knight closer to e3, allows White to stay in control.} 10. Nxe5 {
Exchanging the knight on c6 in order to enable b2-b4 soon.} ({The typical} 10.
fxe5 Ng4 11. Bg5 {fails to bother the black queen:} Qb6 12. Nb5 Ncxe5 13. a4 {
Afkham Ebrahimi,P-Zebrowski,B Philadelphia 2008 (½-½, 43)} a5 $1 {Black has
stabilized the queenside and the kingside mainly offers him active
possibilities.}) 10... Nxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 {Black has to put an eye on the enemy
kingside.} (11... Nd7 12. b4 $14) 12. Nc2 $1 $146 {Not only threatening b2-b4,
but also preparing e5-e6 under favourable circumstances.} (12. e6 {is
premature:} Bxe6 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bg2 (14. Bd5 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Qxd5 $17 {Bachler,
R (2205)-Weinberger,S (2008) Graz 2014 (½-½, 35)}) 14... Be5 $1 {Suddenly
the threat ...Nxh2 is hard to meet.} 15. h3 Ne3 16. Bxe3 dxe3 $17) 12... Bxe5 (
12... a5 {already allows} 13. e6 {as e3 is well defended.} fxe6 (13... Bxe6 14.
Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bg2 Be5 16. h3 $14) 14. Rxf8+ Qxf8 15. Bd2 a4 (15... Bd7 16. h3
Nh6 17. Bxa5 $14) 16. h3 Nh6 17. g4 Bd7 18. b4 axb3 19. axb3 {with pleasant
play for White.}) 13. h3 Nf6 14. b4 Nh5 {Black has lost the queenside battle
as he cannot consolidate with ...b7-b6, so he throws himself into a desperate
counter-attack.} (14... cxb4 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Rxf4 $14 {dooms the pawn on d4.})
15. g4 Ng3 16. Bf4 $1 {The simplest way to neutralize Black's attack..} Nxf1
17. Bxe5 Qg5 (17... Ne3 18. Nxe3 dxe3 19. bxc5 $18 {leaves Black awfully
passive and with his king vulnerable.}) 18. Bd6 Ne3 19. Nxe3 Qxe3+ 20. Qf2
Qxf2+ 21. Kxf2 cxb4 (21... Rd8 22. bxc5 {is hopeless.}) 22. Bxb4 Rd8 23. Bc5 {
[%cal Ga1b1] Black is an exchange up and pawns are equal, but his position
remains joyless, as there is no obvious way of completing the queenside
development. White's next move would be Rb1.} *

