{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 d4 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c4 Re8 {Since White has enough resources
after the immediate opening of the centre, Black considers preparing it with
his last move.} 10. Rb1 $146 {After examining a series of alternatives, I came
to the conclusion that this untested move is the most effective. The idea is
simple: after ...e7-e5 the knight will jump away from c6 so White should be
ready to play b2-b4 under the best circumstances.} e5 ({It does not make too
much sense to postpone the pawn break. Among the half waiting moves, I can
hardly think of anything else than} 10... Rb8 {but this creates some problems
along the h2-b8 diagonal.} 11. h3 {White starts his kingside play, showing
that he is not in zugzwang at all.} e5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 {We can see
another merit of h2-h3: the knight cannot jump to g4 already.} ({And of course
} 13... Rxe5 14. Bf4 {wins the exchange.}) 14. e6 Rxe6 (14... fxe6 {leads to a
favourable structure for White, who does not need to care about the pressure
on e2 anymore, while the control over e4 is promising.} 15. Nb5 a6 16. Nd6 Rf8
17. Bf4 $14 {White can exchange on c8 at any time but on the way, he tries to
provoke ...e6-e5 so that his g2-bishop would be even stronger.}) 15. Bd5 Rf6 ({
The exchange sacrifice offers Black some compensation, but in principle White
should keep the upper hand.} 15... Ne5 16. Bxe6 Bxe6 17. g4 Qe7 18. Qg3 Re8 19.
b4 cxb4 20. Nc2 Nc6 21. a3 bxa3 22. Bxa3 Qd7 23. Bd6 $14) (15... Re7 {loses
the exchange under much worse circumstances to} 16. Bg5 $16) 16. Bg5 $1 {
Only a pseudo-sacrifice.} Rxf1+ 17. Qxf1 Qf8 (17... Bf6 18. h4 Qe7 19. Qf4 $16
{with better development and strong pressure.}) (17... Qxg5 $2 18. Qxf7+ Kh8
19. Qg8#) 18. Nb5 {with a general invasion.}) 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. fxe5 Ng4 13. b4
{The consequent sequel of 10.Rb1. Due to the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal
Black cannot keep his structure compact with ...b7-b6. Instead, he is bound to
find dynamic resources to compensate for the strategic problems.} Nxe5 ({If} 
13... Bxe5 14. h3 Ne3 15. Bxe3 dxe3 16. bxc5 {The extra pawn on c5 is
temporary, but the pawn on e3 is a clear target.} Qg5 ({Provoking the next
move after which the bishop on g2 will be temporarily passive. If} 16... Qe7
17. Bd5 Rf8 18. Nc2 $16) 17. Rf3 {Planning Nc2.} Qe7 (17... Bg7 {can be met
with} 18. Qa5 {followed by Qc7, a manoeuvre allowed by the bishop's retreat.})
18. Nc2 Qxc5 19. Kh2 $14 {Due to the threat Rb5 Black cannot keep his pawn on
e3. The weakness of the white kingside offers him just some compensation.}) (
13... cxb4 {helps White to activate his play.} 14. Rxb4 Bxe5 15. Bxb7 $1 {
Not fearing any ghosts. Clearing the square on g2 for the king is essential in
anticipation of ...Nxh2.} Bxb7 (15... Nxh2 16. Bxa8 Nxf1 17. Kxf1 {and Black
does not have enough resources to continue his attack.}) 16. Rxb7 Nxh2 17. Kxh2
Qh4+ 18. Kg2) 14. Qf2 cxb4 15. Rxb4 {The pawn on d4 is in some danger now.} Qe7
{Defending f7 in order to allow ...Nc6, covering d4.} (15... Rb8 16. Nc2 $16)
16. Rb3 Ng4 {Before bringing the knight to c6 Black tries to force the enemy
queen onto a worse position.} ({If} 16... Nc6 17. Bg5 $1 {offers White strong
initiative.}) 17. Qf3 Ne5 (17... Ne3 18. Bxe3 dxe3 19. Nb5 $16 {Threatens not
only the elegant Nd6 but also the simple Nc3 when after the forced exchange
White has excellent play due to the pressure on b7 and his mobile centre.}) 18.
Qf4 Nc6 {Now that g5 is not available anymore, the knight finally retreats to
defend the pawn.} 19. Nb5 Be5 20. Qf2 $14 {White has excellent coordination
and a series of threats such as Ba3, Bd5, or even the prosaic Bxc6 followed by
Nxd4 in some cases.} *

