{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 d4 8. Na3 Nc6 9. c4 Rb8 {The same as in the Leningrad Dutch,
this seems to be the most consistent plan. True, the plan based on ...dxc3 and
...b7-b5 is not available anymore but the last move prepares the harmonious
development with ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7.} 10. Bd2 b6 11. h3 {White is not in a
hurry to prepare b2-b4, as the knight can be useful on a3 still if Black plays
...Qc7 for instance. As we know from an earlier line, the last move not only
prepares g3-g4 but also prepares the intrusion to e3 via g4, for the case
White plays b2-b4 slightly later.} Bb7 12. g4 Ne8 {The knight does not have
great perspectives on f6 and it is obstructing the bishop on g7, too, making
Ne5 a permanent issue.} (12... e6 {Marin,M (2531)-Della Pietra,A (2226) Porto
Mannu 2019 (1-0, 31) This move clears the e7-square for the queen. Indeed,
there are not many comfortable squares for Her Majesty (with the exception of
d8, of course).} 13. Nc2 a5 14. Na3 Qe7 15. Nb5 Rbe8 (15... Ba8 16. a3 a4 17.
Qd1 {wins the pawn on a4.}) 16. a3 a4 17. Ne5 Rc8 (17... Nxe5 18. fxe5 {
wins a piece.}) 18. Qh4 (18. e3 dxe3 19. Bc3 {is also interesting.}) 18... Ba8
19. b4 axb3 20. Rab1 {with constant pressure on both wings.}) ({With White's
kingside plan so advanced, preparing ...e7-e5 is risky:} 12... Re8 13. Qf2 ({
Before undertaking anything concrete White should improve his piece placement
to the maximum. The last move creates a latent pressure along the f-file.} 13.
f5 {is possible, but the following beautiful (and more or less forced)
variation seems to lead only to a draw:} e5 14. fxe6 Rxe6 15. Ng5 Re7 16. Qh4 {
It is hard to find another way of continuing the attack.} Rxe2 17. Rxf6 Qxf6
18. Qxh7+ Kf8 19. Rf1 Qxf1+ $1 {This queen sacrifice weakens the white king's
defence, eventually resulting into a perpetual.} 20. Kxf1 Rxd2 21. Bd5 Ne5 22.
Bxf7 Nxd3 23. Qg8+ Ke7 24. Qxb8 Rf2+ 25. Kg1 Rg2+ 26. Kf1 $11) 13... a6 (13...
e5 {is premature due to} 14. fxe5 Nd7 15. Bg5 Qc8 16. Nb5 $16) 14. f5 e5 15.
Ng5 Ne7 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 17. Qg2 Rd7 18. Ne4 $14 {with pleasant play on the light
squares.}) (12... h5 {fails to force g4-g5, after which Black would have
chances to get the control with ...Ne8-d6-f5.} 13. Qh4 ({Another strong
continuation is} 13. f5 hxg4 14. hxg4 Nxg4 15. Qh4 gxf5 16. Ng5 Nh6 17. Rxf5 {
with a consistent attack. For instance} e6 18. Rf2 Qe7 19. Qe4 {Black's best
is 19...f5 returning the pawn on e6, with a stable advantage for White, as if}
Nf5 20. Rxf5 exf5 21. Qxf5 Rfe8 22. Bd5 Ne5 23. Bxf7+ Nxf7 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Rf1
Bf6 26. Nxf7 Qxf7 27. Rxf6 Qxf6 28. Bh6+ Qxh6 29. Qxh6+ Kg8 30. Nb5 $16 {
the white king is safe (it could hide on d2) While Black's is exposed to the
combined attack of the queen and knight.}) 13... Qd7 14. f5 hxg4 15. hxg4 gxf5
16. Ng5 ({More ambitious than} 16. gxf5 Qxf5 17. Nxd4 Qg6 18. Nf5 {which
should be better for White, too.}) 16... e6 17. gxf5 exf5 18. Bf4 {for the
time being White activates all his pieces, without caring about the material.
The main point is that Black cannot do anything to free his kingside from the
pressure.} Rbe8 19. Nb5 Rxe2 20. Bf3 Rxb2 21. Nd6 $18 {[%cal Gh4h1,Gf3d5]
followed by Qh1 and Bd5 with a decisive attack already.}) 13. f5 Nd6 {Trying
to challenge White on the kingside.} (13... Nc7 {placed the knight on a square
with reduced mobility allowing White to continue improving his position with}
14. Qg3 $14) 14. fxg6 {After the knight's departure from f6, this exchange
weakens Black's kingside.} fxg6 ({The strategically more desirable} 14... hxg6
{offers White a strong attack after} 15. Ng5 Bf6 16. Qh4 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 f6 (
17... Re8 {weakens f7. White can go} 18. Nb5 {threatening Nxd6 followed by
Rxf7 and if} Ne5 19. Bf4 {and Black cannot defend f7 for too long.}) 18. Bd5+
Nf7 19. Rxf6 $1 exf6 20. Bxf6 $18) 15. Ng5 {White truly enjoys the weaknesses
created by ...fxg6.} Rxf1+ 16. Qxf1 Ne5 (16... Qd7 17. Bd5+ Kh8 18. Qf2 h6 19.
Ne6 Ne5 20. Bf4 Nef7 21. b4 $16) 17. Ne6 $1 $146 ({Better than} 17. Bxb7 Rxb7
18. Qg2 Qd7 19. Bf4 Nef7 20. Rf1 Nxg5 21. Bxg5 Nf7 22. Bf4 e5 23. Bg3 {which
is just a bit more pleasant for White, Shivananda, B (2323)-Gagunashvili, M 
(2562) Mumbai 2014 (½-½, 60)}) 17... Bxg2 (17... Qd7 18. Bd5 {is paralyzing.}
) 18. Qxg2 Qd7 19. Qd5 {White has very strong pressure, which he can maintain
even after the following exchanges.} Qc6 20. Bf4 Qxd5 21. cxd5 Nd7 22. Nc4 $14
Nf6 23. Be5 Bh8 24. Bxf6 Bxf6 25. g5 Bh8 26. Nxd6 exd6 27. a4 $16 {with a very
promising ending with a good knight versus a bad bishop.} *

