{[%evp 0,25,26,-18,-18,-18,-5,-58,-43,-43,-37,-35,-36,-43,-17,-61,-5,4,15,-31,
-12,-38,46,46,46,29,56,48]} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O
6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 Nc6 {It is hard to evaluate this move one-sidedly. It is the
most natural developing move but on the other hand it allows White to carry
out his next move effortlessly:} 8. e4 dxe4 {Black is best adviced to react in
the centre at once.} (8... Re8 {preparing ...e7-e5 takes away the e8-square
from the knight, allowing} 9. e5 {under favourable circumstances:} Ng4 (9...
Nd7 10. e6 $14) 10. h3 Nh6 11. g4 $14 {The h6-knight will be out of play for a
while.}) (8... Rb8 {is a bit more flexible but it does not threaten anything
concrete.} 9. Nc3 (9. e5 {is playable, too, even though the knight has a more
flexible path than in the previous line:} Ne8 10. Nc3 Nc7 11. Qf2 b6 12. d4 {
and Black will need some time to activate his g7-bishop, possibly at the cost
of weakening his structure.}) 9... d4 10. Nd1 {We have reached a typical
"improved King's Indian" structure which will be examined in the strategic
article.}) 9. dxe4 e5 {Another logical reaction.} (9... Nd4 {is premature.} 10.
Nxd4 cxd4 (10... Qxd4+ 11. Kh1 Be6 12. Nc3 Rad8 13. h3 $14 {followed by g3-g4.}
) 11. e5 Ng4 12. h3 Nh6 13. g4 Kh8 14. Na3 $16 {Spasov,V (2452)-Gupta,A (2031)
ICCF email 2006 (0-1, 28) Due to Black's passive kingside minor pieces the
pawn on d4 is doomed.}) {Now is the moment to continue the discussion about
the merits of Black's 7...Nc6. With reversed colours, a similar position would
be entirely satisfactory for Black. But with White we are bound to wish a bit
more than that. The main plot gravitates around Black's ...exf4 and White's
fxe5 or f4-f5 and the question remains which is the best move order that
allows White to retain chances for some advantage, or at least consistent play?
} 10. Nc3 ({I hesitated for a long time when choosing between this and} 10. Na3
{The latter is safe, as the knight defends c2 in advance, neutralizing the
threat ...Nd4 in advance. But I could not find more than simple equality after}
exf4 $1 (10... Re8 {allows} 11. f5 gxf5 12. Bg5 {with dangerous initiative.}
fxe4 $6 13. Nd2 Qd4+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 15. Nxe4 $16 {In this line the rook departure
from f8 as well as the extra tempo Na3 (with the idea Nb5, for instance)
change the evaluation with respect of the immediate f4-f5 mentioned below.})
11. Bxf4 Be6 {Preventing Nc4.} 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. e5 Nh5 14. Bc1 Rad8 $11 {
and White cannot transfer his a3-knight to d6, unfortunately.}) (10. f5 {
is premature:} gxf5 11. Nh4 Nxe4 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. Rxf5 Nd6 {unblocking the
centre.}) 10... Be6 {This natural developing move is a bit too inviting.} ({
White is better prepared for} 10... exf4 {than in the line with 10.Na3, as his
knight controls d5.} 11. e5 $1 $146 {White immediately starts the fight for
the d5-square.} (11. Bxf4 {leads to comfortable play but not more.}) 11... Nd5
{Relatively best. Black exchanges the dangerous knight before it intrudes
through d5.} (11... Ng4 12. Bxf4 $14) (11... Re8 12. Bxf4 $14) (11... Nh5 12.
gxf4 Be6 13. Be3 $14) 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. gxf4 {Black is slightly underdeveloped
and his queen is vulnerable.} Nd4 (13... Bf5 14. Be3 $14) 14. Qf2 Nf5 15. Ng5
Qd4 16. Ne4 Qxf2+ 17. Rxf2 c4 {The only way to defend the pawn.} 18. b3 $14 {
The threat bxc4 followed by c4-c5 is serious.} cxb3 19. axb3 {with obvious
queenside pressure.}) (10... Nd4 {This resolute move induces the exchange on
e5, but without developing a piece on the way.} 11. fxe5 Nxf3+ (11... Ng4 12.
Qd1 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Nxe5 14. Qf4 Be6 {Lavis,J (2079)-Rudenko,V (2246) LSS email
2013 (½-½, 47)} 15. Nd5 {with active play.}) (11... Nxc2 $2 12. Qf2 Nxa1 13.
exf6 Qxf6 14. Bf4 $16) 12. Bxf3 Ng4 13. Nd5 Nxe5 14. Bg2 Be6 15. Be3 {It is
hard to tolerate such a knight for too long.} Bxd5 16. exd5 Re8 17. Qf2 b6 18.
Rad1 Qd7 19. Bf4 Ng4 20. Qf3 Bxb2 21. c3 c4 22. d6 $44 {Despite his extra pawn,
Black's position is dangerous, Trapeznikova,D (2101)-Nasybullina,A (2045)
Satka 2017 (1-0, 78)}) (10... Re8 {will be examined in Line 23.}) 11. f5 $1 {
White has no reasons to refuse the invitation.} Bc4 (11... gxf5 12. Bg5 {
offers White too much play.} Re8 (12... fxe4 13. Nxe4 Bg4 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. Rd6
Be6 16. Rxc6 bxc6 17. Nxe5 $18) 13. exf5 $1 $146 (13. Nh4 f4 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15.
exf5 Nd4 {was unclear in Movsziszian,K (2486)-Moroni,L (2553) Porto Mannu 2019
(1-0, 34)}) 13... Bc4 (13... Bxf5 14. Nh4 $18) 14. Rd1 Nd4 (14... Qe7 15. Bxf6
Bxf6 16. Nd2 Bxf1 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Ne4 Bg7 19. Ndf6+) (14... Qa5 15. Qe3 $5 Bxf1
16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne4 Bg7 18. f6 $18 {In all these lines we see a true
symphony on the ligth squares, with influence over the dark squares, too!}) 15.
Rf2 e4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Nxe4 Bd5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Qb4 $16) 12.
Rf2 Ng4 13. Rd2 {A typical rook's trajectory in the Leningrad Dutch. Black has
only exposed his minor pieces on the way.} Nd4 (13... Qa5 14. h3 Nf6 15. g4 h6
16. Rf2 Rae8 17. Nd2 Bb5 (17... Ba6 18. Nb3 Qb6 19. Be3 $16) 18. Nxb5 Qxb5 19.
c3 Qa5 (19... Qb6 20. Nc4 Qc7 21. g5 hxg5 22. Bxg5 Nh7 23. Bh4 Bh6 24. Ne3 $16)
20. Nb3 Qb5 21. Bf1 Qb6 22. g5 hxg5 23. Bxg5 gxf5 24. exf5 {[%cal Gb3d2]} (24.
Rxf5 {Rodriguez Vila,A (2511)-Stamenkovic,D (2393) Villa Martelli 2006 (1-0,
42)} Ne7 25. Rf2 Ng6 $14) 24... e4 25. Bxf6 Bxf6 26. Rg2+ Kh7 27. Qe2 Kh6 28.
Nd2 $16 {with a very strong attack.}) 14. h3 Nh6 15. g4 (15. b3 Ba6 16. g4 $16
{prevents the bishop's retreat home.}) 15... f6 16. Nd1 Nf7 17. c3 Nxf3+ 18.
Bxf3 Qc7 19. Ne3 Ba6 20. Nd5 {The triumph of White's strategy. Black is
strategically lost.} Qa5 (20... Qd6 21. Rd1 $16) 21. Bg2 (21. fxg6 Ng5 22.
gxh7+ Kh8 23. Bg2 $18) (21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Nxg6+ hxg6 23. fxg6 Ng5 24. Qh4+ Kg8
25. Rf2 $18) 21... g5 {Zhao,X (2565)-Zhu,C (2491) Beijing 2012 (1-0, 50)} 22.
