6. d3 c5 7. Qe1 Nc6 8. e4 dxe4 9. dxe4 e5 10. Nc3 Re8 {This developing move,
increasing the pressure in the centre and not really allowing f4-f5 yet, was
the hardest to find a viable continuation against.} 11. fxe5 {The only
constructuve move, speeding up White's development.} (11. f5 Nd4 {more or less
forces} 12. Qd1 {resulting into the loss of two tempi, not really White's
dream.}) 11... Nxe5 (11... Ng4 {is an important alternative.} 12. Nd5 (12. Bg5
Qb6 13. Nd5 Qxb2 {as in Kololli,K (1827)-Sawlin,L (1952) Oberhof 2013 (½-½,
38) offers White reasonable compensation for the pawn..} 14. h3 $5 Ngxe5 15.
Nf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 {This looks dangerous for Black but he can hold his own with
} Re6 17. Nxe5 Rxf6 $1 18. Rxf6 Qxe5 {and it is Black's turn to have good
compensation for the minimal material disadvantage.}) 12... Ngxe5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5
14. Bf4 Be6 15. Rd1 Bxd5 16. Kh1 $5 {By removing the threat ...Nf3+ after exd5,
White keeps the possibility of any re-capture on d5, depending on Black's next
move.}) 12. Nxe5 Qd4+ $1 (12... Rxe5 13. Bf4 {offers White the initiative.} Re8
(13... Re7 14. Rd1 Qb6 15. Rd6 Qxb2 16. Bc1 Qb4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rd8+ Bf8 19.
Bh6 Bd7 20. Rxa8 Be8 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Qf2 $18) {Pancevski,F (2399)
-Schekachikhin,M (1936) Albena 2011 (1-0, 21)} 14. Nb5 $16) 13. Be3 $5 $146 ({
I eventually came to the conclusion that} 13. Qf2 {mainly exposes the white
queen, which is well placed on d1, actually.} Qxe5 14. h3 (14. Nd5 {Bintakies,
M (2139)-Pohl Kuemmel,J (2280) Bayern 2011 (1-0, 67)} Nxe4 15. Qxf7+ Kh8 16.
Bf4 Qd4+ {with equal chances in a still complicated position.}) (14. Bf4 Qh5 {
planning ...Bh3.}) 14... g5 $1 {The best way to meet the threat Bf4. I have
shown this line in order to prepare the reader for a similarly exotic white
move in the main line.}) 13... Qxe5 14. Bf4 Qh5 15. h4 $1 {This is the move I
was talking about! It is essential to tend a net around the black queen and
also prevent ...Bh3, which would weaken the defence of the pawn on e4. In
principle, White threatens Bg5, aiming to invade on d5, after which the queen
would be exposed to Nf4.} h6 {Defending g5 and preparing to open the kingside
in the search for counterplay.} (15... Be6 16. Nb5 Bc4 17. Nc7 Bxf1 18. Qxf1
Nxe4 19. Bf3 Qf5 20. Nxa8 Rxa8 21. Qd3 Nf6 22. Qxf5 gxf5 23. Rd1 Re8 24. c3 $14
{With a pleasant ending despite the missing pawn.}) (15... Bg4 16. Bg5 Re6 (
16... Nd7 17. Nd5 $16) 17. e5 {Threatening Bxf6.} Nd7 (17... Bf5 18. Bxb7 Rb8
19. Bf3 Ng4 20. Ne2 Bxe5 21. Qa5 $14 {With the queen almost trapped on h5, the
queenside is vulnerable.}) 18. Qf2 Rf8 19. Nd5 Bxe5 20. Nf4 Bxf4 21. Qxf4 $14 {
with more than enough compensation for the pawn due to the active bishops and
the unfortunate queen's placement on h5.}) 16. Rd1 g5 17. Bd6 gxh4 (17... Be6 {
allows} 18. e5 Ng4 19. Bxb7 Rab8 20. Bf3 gxh4 21. Nd5 {There is no need to
take on h4 already.} hxg3 22. Qxg3 $16 {with very active play.}) 18. gxh4 Be6
19. Qg3 {Threatening Rxf6.} Qg4 20. Qxg4 Nxg4 21. Bxc5 Rac8 (21... Bxc3 22.
bxc3 Bxa2 23. Ra1 Bc4 24. Rf4 $14) 22. Bd4 Ne5 {Black has certain compensation
for the pawn but White can still fight for an advantage. I would choose} 23.
Rf2 {defending the second rank.} *

