Qc8 {Nakamura,H (2741)-Johannessen,L (2514) Oslo 2010 (1-0, 20)} 10. e4 dxe4
11. Ne5 Nb6 12. g4 $5 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gg4g5] followed by g4-g5 and dxe4.}) 7...
dxe4 8. dxe4 Nxe4 9. Ng5 Nxg5 10. Bxa8 {The pawn on b5 is a weakness, which
makes this position by far more appealing for White than the similar one with .
..b7-b6.} Qxd1 ({Or if} 10... Ne6 11. Bg2 {and Black does not have the quick
counterattack with ...Ba6.}) 11. Rxd1 Bg4 12. Rf1 Na6 13. Bg2 Nh3+ 14. Kh1 Nb4
15. Na3 {Now is a moment when White gains an important tempo by attacking b5.}
a6 (15... Rd8 16. Bf3 $5 h5 17. Bxg4 hxg4 18. Nxb5 Nxc2 19. Rb1 $14) 16. Rb1 c5
17. Be3 $14 {with reasonable chances to convert the extra exchange.}) 7. c3 (7.
Nbd2 {is an attempt to keep things more interesting.} Re8 (7... Qd6 8. e4 dxe4
9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. dxe4 {is pleasant for White. The queen is not especially well
placed on d6.}) (7... d4 8. e4 $5 dxe3 9. Nc4 {Since Black does not have a
pawn on c5, White has chances to gain space in the centre.}) 8. e4 (8. d4 Bf5
9. c3 {would more or less transpose to the main line.}) 8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 e5 (
9... Nxe4 10. dxe4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 e5 12. c3 exf4 13. gxf4 Rxe4 14. Ne5) 10.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. c3 c5 14. Bh6) 7... Re8 (7... Qd6 {
is answered in a similar way as in the main line.} 8. d4 Bf5 (8... Ne4 9. Nbd2
Nxd2 $6 {Bondar,A (2165)-Westerinen,H (2378) Arvier 2006 (0-1, 57)} 10. Nxd2 $1
{[%cal Ge2e4] Threatening e2-e4.} f5 11. Nf3 $14 {The position is almost
symmetrical but White's knight is better placed. Besides, White is the only
one who can plan to undermine the enemy centre with c3-c4.}) 9. Nbd2 Ne4 10. e3
Rad8 11. Qe2 {with similar play as below.}) 8. Ne5 Qd6 9. d4 {This is
